{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17607108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17607108"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:20:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:20:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15949"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15949"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114791"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8640"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15949"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96794"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8706"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22409"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114791"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thyroid gland is a midline structure (Image) and understanding its embryological development will aid in the diagnosis of some of the pathological processes associated with this organ.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the thyroid gland?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["First pharyngeal pouch at the foramen caecum","Second pharyngeal pouch at the base of the tongue","Third pharyngeal pouch alongside the parathyroid glands","Fourth pharyngeal pouch with the ultimobranchial bodies","Fifth pharyngeal pouch near the cricoid cartilage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thyroid gland develops from the endoderm of the \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst pharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E at the foramen caecum, between the anterior two-thirds and posterior third of the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esecond pharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E develops into the palatine tonsils, whilst the \u003Cstrong\u003Ethird pharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to the inferior parathyroid glands and thymus. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efourth pharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E develops into the superior parathyroid glands, and the \u003Cstrong\u003Efifth pharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E is rudimentary in humans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs the thyroid descends from its point of origin to its final position in the neck, it remains connected to the tongue by an epithelial tract called the thyroglossal duct. This duct normally degenerates, but persistence can lead to thyroglossal duct cysts (Image). The thyroid reaches its final position anterior to the trachea by week seven of development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The thyroid gland develops from the endoderm of the first pharyngeal pouch at the foramen caecum.","The thyroglossal duct forms as the thyroid descends from the tongue to its final position in the neck.","The thyroid reaches its final position anterior to the trachea by week seven of development."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Taha A, Enodien B, Frey DM, Taha-Mehlitz S. Thyroglossal Duct Cyst, a Case Report and Literature Review. Diseases. 2022 Jan 25;10(1):7. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8883879/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96794"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15949"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21286"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21287"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21286"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2fJwsT6OKWfT5N7COAePZreq9Z9XX4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2fJwsT6OKWfT5N7COAePZreq9Z9XX4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21287"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GVTLHDYY5BnfFtrvkHAwgITlaNOoAr.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GVTLHDYY5BnfFtrvkHAwgITlaNOoAr.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":317,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96794"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T11:45:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T11:46:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8640"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114791"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attribut